"You Y., Huber M., Müller R.D., Poulsen J., Ribbe J.","Simulation of the middle miocene climate optimum",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","4", L04702,"","",,,10.1029/2008GL036571,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-66149191264&partnerID=40&md5=5bc6e6e68436d61e7bdfbc60023aeabd","Institute of Marine Science, University of Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia; School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia; Department of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN 47907, United States; Department of Geological Sciences, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI 48109, United States; Department of Biological and Physical Sciences, University of Southern Queensland, Toowoomba, QLD 4350, Australia","You, Y., Institute of Marine Science, University of Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia, School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia; Huber, M., Department of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences, Purdue University, West Lafayette, IN 47907, United States; Müller, R.D., School of Geosciences, University of Sydney, NSW 2006, Australia; Poulsen, J., Department of Geological Sciences, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI 48109, United States; Ribbe, J., Department of Biological and Physical Sciences, University of Southern Queensland, Toowoomba, QLD 4350, Australia","Proxy data constraining land and ocean surface paleo-temperatures indicate that the Middle Miocene Climate Optimum (MMCO), a global warming event at ̃15 Ma, had a global annual mean surface temperature of 18.4°C, about 3°C higher than present and equivalent to the warming predicted for the next century. We apply the latest National Center for Atmospheric Research (NCAR) Community Atmosphere Model CAM3.1 and Land Model CLM3.0 coupled to a slab ocean to examine sensitivity of MMCO climate to varying ocean heat fluxes derived from paleo sea surface temperatures (SSTs) and atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations, using detailed reconstructions of Middle Miocene boundary conditions including paleogeography, elevation, vegetation and surface temperatures. Our model suggests that to maintain MMCO warmth consistent with proxy data, the required atmospheric CO2 concentration is about 460-580 ppmv, narrowed from the most recent estimate of 300-600 ppmv. © 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Annual mean; Atmospheric carbon dioxide concentration; Atmospheric CO; Climate optima; Community atmosphere model; Land model; Middle Miocene; National center for atmospheric researches; Ocean heat flux; Ocean surfaces; Paleogeography; Proxy data; Sea surface temperatures; Slab ocean; Surface temperatures; Atmospheric chemistry; Carbon dioxide; Climatology; Global warming; Ocean engineering; Oceanography; Surface properties; Surface waters; Atmospheric temperature; atmospheric modeling; carbon dioxide; climate variation; global warming; Miocene; paleoclimate; paleogeography; proxy climate record; reconstruction; sea surface temperature",,,,,,"Adams, C.G., Lee, D.E., Rosen, B.R., Conflicting isotopic and biotic evidence for tropical searsurface temperatures during the Tertiary (1990) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol, 77, pp. 289-313; Barron, E.J., Peterson, W.H., Model simulation of the Cretaceous ocean circulation (1989) Science, 244, pp. 684-686; Bojar, A.V., Hiden, H., Fenninger, A., Neubauer, F., Middle Miocene temperature changes in the central, paratethys: Relations with the East Antarctica ice sheet development (2005) South American Symposium on Isotope Geology, , paper presented at, Dep. of Geol, Fed. Univ. of Pernambuco, Salvador, Brazil; Ceding, T.E., Carbon dioxide in the atmosphere: Evidence from Cenozoic and Mesozoic paleosols (1991) Am. J. Sci, 291, pp. 377-400; Christophel, D.C., Evolution of the Australian flora through the Tertiary (1989) Plant Syst. Evol, 162, pp. 63-78; Devereux, I., Oxygen isotope paleo-temperature measurements on New Zealand Tertiary fossils (1967) N. Z. J. Sci, 10, pp. 988-1011; Flower,